## Creative Label decision order

1. Ignore canceled tasks as evidence.
2. If the mechanic/Creative structure never existed: **New promo**.
3. If an existing structure needs a different visual theme: **New theme for promo**.
4. Otherwise, if an art-visible prize, mission, value, percentage, quantity, or multiplier changes: **Prize Change**.
5. Otherwise: **Reuse**.

Theme change wins when theme and prize both change. Dynamic configuration that is not embedded in art may remain Reuse. A missing reference does not change the label. A confirmed matching promo/variant previously live on the Operation - Monetization board is valid Reuse evidence; when no exact Creative reference exists, link the Ops task and record its live date. Do not use a different visible variant as evidence.

## Mandatory workflow

For **Reuse**, create one bare day-level item named `REUSE - No Creative Action`. Its single parent update lists every Reuse promotion for that day with promotion title, reuse-from date, and the exact Creative reference. When that reference is unavailable but Ops confirms the promo went live, use the Ops task link and live date. Do not duplicate templates, create per-promo Reuse items, or create asset subitems for Reuse.

For **every real MGAP promotion**, also create a separate parent named `MGAP UI - <variant>` in the same day group, regardless of whether the regular MGAP promo is active or listed in Reuse. The MGAP UI parent is additional work, never a replacement for the regular task/summary row. Keep only UI-related subitems and remove other duplicated assets. This also applies when MGAP is embedded in another offer, such as a Rolling MGAP ladder. Do not create it for RLAP/Stash Booster; Stash replaces the daily MGAP promo.

For every non-Reuse promo:

1. Find template on board (Coins Sale, Dynamic JP, Buy All, Daily Deal, RYD, Rolling Offer, PYP, MES, etc.)
2. `duplicate_item(board_id, item_id)` — do not invent `create_item` + duplicate id
3. `change_multiple_column_values` — name, promo date, due dates, team, and blank art path; Product only if label exists
4. `move_item_to_group` — user’s group (duplicate often lands in Templates)
5. `create_update` on parent — exactly two rows: Creative Label and Change
6. `create_update` on **every subitem** — briefs live in updates, not description (duplication does not copy subitem updates)
7. Clear every surviving subitem's Copy Status, Art Status, TL Approval, and Subject Line
8. Wait for board automation, then re-query; remove strays and verify dates/team

## References

- **Reference** and **Reference Link** are always separate rows. **Reference** contains only the real embedded PNG/image preview; **Reference Link** contains only its direct URL or exact CRM3 file path.
- **Reference Link** = direct attached-image URL or full file path: `Q:\Slotomania\CRM3\...\filename.png` (not folder-only)
- **Reference** = embedded preview: upload from CRM3 via `add_file_to_update` → `/v2/file`, then optional `edit_update` with `https://playtika.monday.com/protected_static/7996532/resources/{asset_id}/{filename}`
- Reference art must match the subitem asset type: Inapp→Inapp, Banner→Banner, Widget→Widget, etc. Never reuse one generic preview across unlike assets.
- Prefer a Reuse reference that visibly contains the exact current prize/theme. If none exists, an exact matching live Ops task is sufficient evidence; show its link and live date without attaching a misleading image.
- Prefer an older exact promo match over a newer same-family task with a different prize or theme. Within the selected exact task, use the latest update that actually contains Creative attachments and the latest relevant attachment(s) from that update.
- Creative's latest attached deliverable outranks an older attachment, an old `Reference Link`, or art merely mentioned in brief text. Record source promo date, pulse/update, and asset.
- The newest delivered attachment may be used before task approval. Never use a canceled task as evidence or reference.
- If the latest Creative update contains multiple required variants, show all of them. Use an older asset only with an explicit reason.
- If no matching historical asset exists, say so explicitly and leave the preview empty; never attach a misleading reference.
- For art briefs use the promo date the user wants (not “exclude incomplete today” analytics rules)

## Brief standards

- Keep briefs short. Do not repeat Promo Date, due dates, priority, category, history, or status details already stored in columns.
- Reuse is consolidated into the single day-level `REUSE - No Creative Action` item; do not create separate Reuse parent tasks.
- Seasonal parent title must include the exact required reward; never leave it only as “Season”.
- Parent brief has exactly two rows: `Creative Label` and `Change`. `Change` states `source → required`; there is no parent reference, asset list, or skeleton row.
- Every subitem body is only one HTML table. Follow the asset-specific schema in `BRIEF_WRITING_STANDARDS.md`; add no prose before or after it.
- Standalone MGAP UI tasks use Product `MGAP`, blank Status Creative, Status MM `Brief Done`, the day’s Creative Traffic assignments, and exactly the UI-related subitem(s).
- Theme cells contain the theme name only. Never include colors, motifs, mood, composition, copy suggestions, or quoted headlines.
- Do not keep no-action subitems in new briefs; request only the assets that need work.
- A Link field contains only the URL or exact CRM3 file path—no commentary, provenance prose, or folder instructions.
- A PNG/reference-art field contains only a real attached image for that exact asset type. If no real matching image exists, omit the row; never create a placeholder or made-up template.
- Before writing any Creative instruction, read the latest comparable parent brief and all relevant subitem updates. Derive the required asset scope and wording from what was actually requested/delivered last time—not from the duplicated template alone.
- Use history to determine the instruction, but do not paste the research into the brief. Summarize it only as concise **Change** and **Keep** rows.
- If the latest comparable execution used only a subset of template assets, request only that subset. Mark the other duplicated subitems Completed/No Action unless Itay explicitly expands scope.
- **Win Master exception:** when driven by M.E.S (Mission Event System), open the complete M.E.S asset set every time. Never reduce it to Banner-only from recent execution history.
- Never infer a missing CTA, version, timer, FP, message, or asset. Use an older matching execution only when the latest task lacks that asset, and document the fallback; otherwise leave it for Itay.
- Coin Sale: include PU / IC / DPU / NPU coin % tiers unless user overrides
- State theme + mechanic clearly; art folder under `Features\...` or `Holidays & Events\{Event}\{year}\Coin_Sale`
- Every subitem must name its asset and point to the parent's exact Change; the parent carries the full delta so it is not repeated in every asset brief.
- **Prize Change**: state `Current/source prize → Required prize` once in the parent, including exact quantity, tier, mission, percentage, and currency. Asset subitems point to that Change.
- **New theme for promo**: state `Current/source theme → Required theme` once in the parent. Do not prescribe motifs, palette, mood, composition, logo treatment, or copy; the reference carries the visual cue.
- **New promo**: do not invent mechanics, prizes, copy, or art direction. Create a clearly marked skeleton for **Itay to complete**; attach only clearly relevant latest references as optional inspiration.
- The parent **Change** row is the shared Creative request; do not add a second repetitive Creative Request or Assets row.
- **Reuse**: the day summary names each exact source promo/date and includes the exact Creative reference or Ops live evidence. The summary has no subitems, Status Creative=`done`, and Status MM=`Ready - no action needed`.
- Never set Copy Status=`Done` merely because the brief was written.
- For every non-Reuse item, leave parent Status Creative empty. Monetization only writes Status MM: `Brief Done` for a complete brief or `MM work in progress` for an incomplete New promo skeleton.
- Art-only required asset: leave both Copy Status and Art Status empty.
- If copy work is explicitly required, use the real active Copy status; set `Done` only after the copy itself is completed.
- Due dates: use Creative Traffic `Brief Date` when available. If unavailable, use the Israeli Sun–Sat fallback: promo Wed–Sat → Art Due Monday of that week; promo Sun–Tue → Art Due Wednesday of the prior week; Brief Due = Art Due − 7 days, shifted from Friday/Saturday back to Thursday. Never invent an invalid date.
- Priority default: Critical for business-critical launch with no fallback; High for new promo/theme or broad anchor package; Medium for prize/mission changes; Low for Reuse, backup, or no-action work. Override only with explicit business context.
- If CRM3 not mounted: set paths and note “upload previews when CRM3 available”

## Mutation guard and subitem reset

- Before renaming, re-finalizing, changing columns, replacing updates/references, deleting/recreating/reordering subitems, or otherwise editing an existing brief, query `color_mkwes65f` (`Status MM`).
- A non-blank Status MM means the brief is in flight. Stop, report the item and status, and ask Itay. Override only after explicit approval and log that approval.
- After writing each surviving subitem, blank all four fields on subitem board `18112200937`: `status` (Copy Status), `color_mkwerpn6` (Art Status), `color_mkwe6hz` (TL Approval), and `long_text_mkwyvrm1` (Subject Line).
- Do not mark Copy or Art Done merely because the brief was authored.

## User request handling

Ask only if missing: theme, promo date, group, SKUs/mechanics, or a promo definition absent from the canonical glossary. Ask unknown promotions one at a time.

Return: Monday pulse URL, item name, date, art path, subitems briefed.

